            "creation_date": 1361374949,
            "body": "<p>There is no direct way to cancel all background threads.<\/p>\n\n<p>OnStop or onDistroy of your activity you need to call below method to stop AsyncTask.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>asyncTask.stop(boolean)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Well, it will not directly stop you asyncTask but in doInBackground method you need to keep on checking for <a href=\"http://developer.android.com/reference/android/os/AsyncTask.html#isCancelled%28%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">isCancelled<\/a> value, if its true then just end the doInBackground and skip postExecute for appropriate return value in status. This is the only way in my knowledge.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 14983948,
            "question_id": 14983777
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7cf5d6b1910c17d8e5b2aae347a6b7e1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1828499,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1660601,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1660601/user1660601",
                "reputation": 273,
                "display_name": "user1660601",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1361378000,
            "creation_date": 1361378000,
            "body": "<p>You can override onPause() in the activity to stop the threads.<\/p>\n\n<p>So you can do:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>@Override    \npublic void onPause(){\n    super.onPause()\n    // Stop threads here\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>And recreate them in onResume(). <\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 14985033,
            "question_id": 14983777
        }
    ],
